			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: How much song range extension is too much?<a name="74434"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 14 05 11:00 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>     How you spend your AAs depends on your play style. If you raid often, or are the only bard on a raid, then extended range is very important. If you are a melee bard, or in a pre-elemental guild, or do not raid much, or your raids usually have more than 2 bards, then it is not so important. I have seen Magelos of bards with over 150 AA and no extended range or instrument/singing mastery, but with a bunch of offensive melee AAs. That is not wrong for their play style.
<br />

<br />
     If you raid a lot, the advantages of covering more people with your songs outweigh the disadvantages of accidentally hitting the feign death pullers. (And yes, I've nearly wiped the raid a couple of times because I hit the FD puller with manasong. Fading Memories helps a bit when your song hits the puller.) The way I test my maximum range is to stand in the Plane of Knowledge near the bank and see who I hit with manasong.
<br />

<br />
     As for my guild, usually there are only 1-2 bards on raids (sometimes 0, sometimes 4.), so extended range is very helpful. The raid is often divided into melee and caster bunches so the casters can avoid the AE rampages (and sometimes the targeted AEs).
<br />

<br />
Section 4 of The Complete Bard AA Guide has a nice guide to AAs depending on your play style.
<br />
http://www.eqdiva.com/Forums/ShowPost.aspx?PostID=65998</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
